WEBVTT

00:06.615 --> 00:09.879
Meredith: Metastatic.
Advanced. Progressed.

00:09.922 --> 00:11.576
All words no one wants to hear
from their doctor.

00:11.620 --> 00:13.361
I can't see anything.
There's too many adhesions.

00:13.404 --> 00:14.797
Retractor.

00:14.840 --> 00:16.364
Retractor!

00:16.407 --> 00:18.453
That seems a little basic,
don't we think?

00:18.496 --> 00:20.237
I swear, this place has gone
down the pipes.

00:20.281 --> 00:22.022
It means despite
everything you've done,

00:22.065 --> 00:23.458
every rule
you've followed,

00:23.501 --> 00:24.807
you may be near the end.

00:24.850 --> 00:25.895
I still don't have
visualization.

00:25.938 --> 00:28.115
Maybe if I can mobilize
the liver --

00:28.158 --> 00:30.117
Ellis: Maybe? That's what
everyone wants in a surgeon.

00:30.160 --> 00:31.770
They maybeknow
what they're doing.

00:31.814 --> 00:33.381
Always have a plan --
I told you that.

00:33.424 --> 00:34.860
[ Monitor alarm ]Suction, Meredith!

00:34.904 --> 00:36.340
It's the moment
when fear sets in.

00:36.384 --> 00:38.473
You panic as you realize
you may not survive.

00:38.516 --> 00:39.561
You're losing control.

00:39.604 --> 00:41.041
I know what I'm doing.

00:41.084 --> 00:42.216
If you did,
you would have done it already.

00:42.259 --> 00:44.087
Give me that.[ Thunder crashes ]

00:44.131 --> 00:45.436
It's why people turn
to experimental treatments

00:45.480 --> 00:47.351
and last-ditch efforts.

00:47.395 --> 00:49.397
Things haven't changed here.
I have to do everything myself.

00:49.440 --> 00:50.572
Clamp.

00:50.615 --> 00:52.269
If you knew you were dying...

00:52.313 --> 00:53.575
[ Gasps ]

00:53.618 --> 00:54.663
...what would you do?

00:56.273 --> 00:59.407
If someone gave you a lifeline,
would you take it?

00:59.450 --> 01:01.670
[ Thunder crashing ]

01:03.106 --> 01:05.065
If it weren't
for the accreditation council,

01:05.108 --> 01:08.068
I'd say that
we should call in sick.

01:08.111 --> 01:11.245
Stay in bed allday.[ Chuckles ]

01:11.288 --> 01:13.290
Mmm.

01:20.732 --> 01:22.299
What are you thinking?

01:25.563 --> 01:27.087
I should go to Boston.

01:27.130 --> 01:29.219
I've called Nana Ante
and my cousins,

01:29.263 --> 01:30.916
the few people I know
Wendell still talks to.

01:30.960 --> 01:32.266
They all think
that he's back in Boston.

01:32.309 --> 01:33.441
Winston --

01:33.484 --> 01:34.485
I'm gonna get
your money back.

01:34.529 --> 01:36.096
Maybe you don't.

01:36.139 --> 01:38.141
Maybe you just
let Wendell have it

01:38.185 --> 01:40.143
and let him get out
of whatever trouble he's in

01:40.187 --> 01:42.754
and -- and -- and we just
go back to our lives.

01:42.798 --> 01:44.147
My brother
stole from you.

01:44.191 --> 01:45.888
[ Sighs ]
My wife.

01:45.931 --> 01:48.282
It's wrong, and he knows it,
and I-I want to fix it.

01:48.325 --> 01:51.198
I need to fix it.No, no. It's fine.

01:51.241 --> 01:52.851
Just let it go.
I don't want you involved

01:52.895 --> 01:53.852
in whatever
he is mixed up in.

01:53.896 --> 01:55.158
It's not fine, Maggie.

01:55.202 --> 01:56.116
It's not fine.

01:56.159 --> 01:57.552
[ Thunder rumbles ]

01:57.595 --> 01:59.293
Please don't tell me
how to handle my brother.

01:59.336 --> 02:01.686
Alright? You have sisters,
but they're not --

02:01.730 --> 02:03.340
What? They're not actually
my sisters?

02:04.994 --> 02:06.300
You didn't grow up
with them.

02:06.343 --> 02:07.649
So that makes them
less my sisters?

02:07.692 --> 02:08.737
No, I -- [ Sighs ]

02:08.780 --> 02:09.912
That's not what I meant.

02:09.955 --> 02:13.220
♪♪

02:13.263 --> 02:15.874
Bailey's gonna lose it
if we're late today.

02:15.918 --> 02:20.052
♪♪

02:20.096 --> 02:21.924
Zola: Ooh,
that one has a sauna.

02:21.967 --> 02:23.621
When have you been
in a sauna?

02:23.665 --> 02:25.232
I read that
it's good for circulation.

02:25.275 --> 02:26.885
It is.

02:26.929 --> 02:28.191
So's biking.

02:28.235 --> 02:29.453
When have youridden
a bike?

02:29.497 --> 02:31.194
[ Door closes ][ Laughs ]

02:31.238 --> 02:34.589
[ Sighs ] Gotta say,
I am not gonna miss this rain.

02:34.632 --> 02:36.286
You've only been here
30 days.

02:36.330 --> 02:37.809
Yeah, and it's rained
for like 26 of them.

02:37.853 --> 02:39.855
[ Laughs ] True.

02:39.898 --> 02:41.857
If the accreditation
council

02:41.900 --> 02:43.293
okays the residency program
today,

02:43.337 --> 02:44.599
does that mean
we're leaving?

02:45.687 --> 02:47.036
Soon.

02:47.079 --> 02:47.993
Amelia:
It's out. It's out.

02:48.037 --> 02:50.431
It's here. Look.

02:50.474 --> 02:52.215
Oh, it's out.

02:52.259 --> 02:53.434
Nick: The Parkinson's treatment
article?

02:53.477 --> 02:55.131
Wow. Nice.[ Zola claps ]

02:55.175 --> 02:57.307
♪♪

02:57.351 --> 02:58.961
Wow.

02:59.004 --> 03:00.310
[ Thunder rumbling ]

03:00.354 --> 03:02.138
[ Siren wails in distance ]

03:02.182 --> 03:05.228
You know, you don't have to
walk us all the way to the door.

03:05.272 --> 03:06.751
We can handle the rain.

03:06.795 --> 03:08.318
Well,
I'm a full-service guy.

03:08.362 --> 03:10.625
As you know.

03:10.668 --> 03:12.409
Last night was amazing.

03:12.453 --> 03:15.282
It...was.

03:15.325 --> 03:17.501
So I'll see you tonight?

03:17.545 --> 03:18.633
Um, maybe.

03:18.676 --> 03:20.896
It depends on work.

03:20.939 --> 03:22.114
Alright.

03:27.294 --> 03:30.122
[ Luna crying ][ Jo sighs ]

03:30.166 --> 03:32.734
Aww, is she tired?

03:32.777 --> 03:36.216
Yeah, she, uh,
didn't sleep well last night.

03:36.259 --> 03:37.652
Teething?
Todd.

03:37.695 --> 03:38.696
Oh.

03:38.740 --> 03:40.263
He's staying over now?

03:40.307 --> 03:42.134
First time.
Probably the last.

03:42.178 --> 03:44.311
Things not going
so well?

03:44.354 --> 03:45.529
Is he not so nice?

03:45.573 --> 03:46.530
Should I be worried?
No.

03:46.574 --> 03:49.098
He's nice,
he's just...

03:49.141 --> 03:51.709
We, uh -- We had sex
for the first time

03:51.753 --> 03:54.321
and he told me
he loved me.

03:54.364 --> 03:55.626
Hmm.

03:55.670 --> 03:56.801
Did you say it back?

03:56.845 --> 03:59.239
Love is a big word
for me.

03:59.282 --> 04:00.979
Right.

04:04.896 --> 04:06.724
He also sings.

04:06.768 --> 04:08.073
Loudly.
I sing.

04:08.117 --> 04:11.294
Um, he sings
when he's...

04:11.338 --> 04:13.514
finished.

04:13.557 --> 04:15.342
He woke up Luna.

04:15.385 --> 04:17.387
O-Oh, oh!

04:17.431 --> 04:18.954
Wow. [ Chuckles ]
[ Sighs ]

04:18.997 --> 04:20.477
[ Clears throat ]

04:20.521 --> 04:21.826
Is it show tunes?

04:21.870 --> 04:23.611
Jazz?
'90s Seattle grunge?

04:23.654 --> 04:27.484
No. It's more like
one long note.

04:27.528 --> 04:28.790
So like --

04:28.833 --> 04:32.097
♪ Do, re, mi, fa, Jo

04:32.141 --> 04:34.926
[ Laughs ] Are you gonna
break up with him at lunch

04:34.970 --> 04:35.927
or after work?[ Elevator bell dings ]

04:35.971 --> 04:38.800
Just forget
I even told you.

04:38.843 --> 04:41.933
♪ Goodby-y-y-ye

04:41.977 --> 04:44.545
Kristen: [ Laughs ]
So you dropped your glasses

04:44.588 --> 04:47.678
in one patient and left
a guide wire in the other one?

04:47.722 --> 04:51.291
Well, I have also had plenty of
really great days, too, I swear.

04:51.334 --> 04:54.206
[ Laughter ]Yeah, they're just not as funny
in the retelling.

04:54.250 --> 04:57.340
[ Laughter ]

04:57.384 --> 04:59.342
So, how are you feeling,
Simon?

04:59.386 --> 05:01.344
Outstanding.

05:01.388 --> 05:04.739
I might jump in that triathlon
out in Bellingham this Saturday.

05:04.782 --> 05:08.308
Unless my son shows up,
but he's taking his sweet time.

05:08.351 --> 05:09.396
Mm-hmm.

05:09.439 --> 05:11.572
[ Chuckles ]
Well, listen up.

05:11.615 --> 05:13.008
Check your e-mails.

05:13.051 --> 05:14.488
Many elective surgeries
were postponed

05:14.531 --> 05:16.228
due to
the acute blood shortage.

05:16.272 --> 05:18.100
We're setting up
a donation center.

05:18.143 --> 05:21.364
In the meantime,
Jamarah Blake returns today.

05:21.408 --> 05:23.975
And, God willing, today's the
day we'll get our program back.

05:24.019 --> 05:26.369
-[ Sighs ] Yes.
-Oh, thank God.

05:26.413 --> 05:28.937
I'll donate.
Sign me up.

05:30.460 --> 05:32.941
Oh, come on, I'm dying.

05:32.984 --> 05:35.073
Someone laugh
at my jokes.

05:35.117 --> 05:36.684
[ Laughs ]

05:36.727 --> 05:37.598
[ Chuckles ][ Clears throat ]

05:37.641 --> 05:38.729
[ Residents chuckle ]

05:41.210 --> 05:43.255
[ Radio chatter ]

05:43.299 --> 05:44.561
Can we mop up this area
by the doors?

05:44.605 --> 05:46.563
Two kids
have slipped already.

05:46.607 --> 05:49.218
Hey, did the blood bank
send out any more O-neg?

05:49.261 --> 05:50.611
They said there's no more
left to send.

05:50.654 --> 05:52.090
Oh. [ Sighs ]
We're gonna have to consider

05:52.134 --> 05:53.657
closing to trauma
unless something changes.

05:53.701 --> 05:54.876
Can you bring
the construction worker

05:54.919 --> 05:56.051
from trauma two upstairs,
please?

05:56.094 --> 05:57.444
Yep.Woman: Here you go, Doctor.

05:57.487 --> 05:58.836
Thanks.

05:58.880 --> 05:59.794
John: Dr. Hunt?

05:59.837 --> 06:01.186
Yeah?

06:01.230 --> 06:02.449
Dr. Owen Hunt?

06:02.492 --> 06:03.450
Yes, can I help you?

06:03.493 --> 06:05.495
My wife.

06:05.539 --> 06:07.758
She's a Marine,
and she's really sick.

06:10.500 --> 06:12.546
Heather Young said
you could help us.

06:12.589 --> 06:18.116
♪♪

06:18.160 --> 06:20.336
Rosie did three tours
in Iraq,

06:20.380 --> 06:21.729
and when she returned
from the last one,

06:21.772 --> 06:23.165
she had this awful cough.

06:23.208 --> 06:24.688
She did a couple rounds
of steroids,

06:24.732 --> 06:26.298
but nothing really helped.

06:26.342 --> 06:28.518
At first they diagnosed her
with chronic bronchitis,

06:28.562 --> 06:29.954
but eventually...

06:29.998 --> 06:31.869
Pulmonary fibrosis.
Yeah.

06:31.913 --> 06:33.784
Well, Pirfenidone has been shown
to slow down

06:33.828 --> 06:35.264
lung function decline.

06:35.307 --> 06:36.657
Rosie couldn't tolerate
the side effects.

06:36.700 --> 06:38.267
Has she tried
pulmonary rehab?

06:38.310 --> 06:39.529
We've tried everything.

06:42.314 --> 06:44.142
I can tell you a little about
the study that we're doing,

06:44.186 --> 06:46.057
but if Rosie would like
to enroll,

06:46.101 --> 06:48.103
I'm gonna have to examine her
in person.

06:48.146 --> 06:49.409
I'm not here
about the study.

06:52.890 --> 06:54.457
♪♪

06:54.501 --> 06:55.893
We live in Utah.

06:55.937 --> 06:57.852
They don't have
physician-assisted death,

06:57.895 --> 07:00.898
and my wife is
in terrible pain.

07:00.942 --> 07:03.031
She can't eat,
she can't sleep.

07:04.380 --> 07:05.337
She's dying.

07:07.383 --> 07:09.603
She needs those medications
you gave the other vets.

07:09.646 --> 07:11.387
John, I don't know
what Heather told you --

07:11.431 --> 07:13.215
She doesn't want to feel like
she's committing suicide.

07:13.258 --> 07:14.869
She wants death
with dignity.

07:14.912 --> 07:17.219
She needs yourhelp.

07:19.482 --> 07:20.701
Please.

07:22.790 --> 07:24.008
John...

07:25.967 --> 07:27.751
I'm sorry, but I can't.

07:27.795 --> 07:33.104
♪♪

07:33.148 --> 07:36.804
If you don't give me the drugs
for my wife,

07:36.847 --> 07:38.632
I'll report
what you've done.

07:38.675 --> 07:47.945
♪♪

07:59.435 --> 08:02.917
Bailey: Thank you for coming,
everyone. I'll get right to it.

08:02.960 --> 08:05.702
So, you are all aware that blood
has been in short supply

08:05.746 --> 08:06.834
since the pandemic.

08:06.877 --> 08:08.662
With the weather
being what it is

08:08.705 --> 08:10.533
and a few heavy traumas
this past week,

08:10.577 --> 08:13.493
our supply has fallen
to critical levels.

08:13.536 --> 08:15.233
So I've asked
the coordinators

08:15.277 --> 08:17.497
to reschedule
all elective surgeries,

08:17.540 --> 08:19.847
and we've also called
state blood banks

08:19.890 --> 08:22.284
and are working on getting
an emergency delivery.

08:22.327 --> 08:24.591
In the meantime,
I want to see butts in seats,

08:24.634 --> 08:25.809
needles in arms.

08:25.853 --> 08:27.550
Tell your friends.

08:27.594 --> 08:30.553
Okay. People's blood
isn't gonna donate itself.

08:30.597 --> 08:31.641
Ex-- Excuse me.

08:31.685 --> 08:34.209
I'm the chief.
I'm first.

08:34.252 --> 08:36.472
Woman: [ Over P.A. ]
Dr. Bradford
to labor and delivery.

08:36.516 --> 08:38.518
Dr. Bradford
to labor and delivery.

08:38.561 --> 08:40.868
I thought blood drives just
give you one cookie, two tops.

08:40.911 --> 08:42.870
What's this?
Because I'm chief
of general.

08:42.913 --> 08:44.088
It comes with perks.
Ah.

08:44.132 --> 08:45.525
Congrats on the article,
Dr. Grey.

08:45.568 --> 08:46.482
Thank you, Karen.

08:46.526 --> 08:48.223
Hey, take a look at this.

08:48.266 --> 08:49.659
48-year-old female,

08:49.703 --> 08:51.966
CT shows a 12-centimeter
pancreatic head tumor

08:52.009 --> 08:53.663
that involves the liver,
the duodenum,

08:53.707 --> 08:56.405
and causing thrombosis
of the portal vein.

08:56.448 --> 08:57.972
Wow.
Yeah, the tumor's

08:58.015 --> 09:00.061
literally at the juncture of
all her internal organs.

09:00.104 --> 09:01.453
If it gets any larger,
she'll be at risk

09:01.497 --> 09:03.586
for catastrophic bleeding,
so it's bad.

09:03.630 --> 09:04.979
Or obstruction.

09:05.022 --> 09:06.937
Yeah, um,
but you don't think a Whipple

09:06.981 --> 09:08.373
would work in this case,
do you?

09:08.417 --> 09:09.984
Are you asking
my opinion?

09:10.027 --> 09:11.115
Well, no. I know you're famous
and everything now,

09:11.159 --> 09:13.988
but I thought
I might still have an in.

09:14.031 --> 09:15.946
Well, you could try
a traditional Whipple,

09:15.990 --> 09:17.948
but I don't even think
you'd get clear margins.

09:17.992 --> 09:18.906
Mm.

09:21.212 --> 09:22.518
Can I meet her?
Take a look?

09:22.562 --> 09:24.215
See? You fell
right into my trap.

09:24.259 --> 09:26.435
Lucky for you,
it's my favorite trap.

09:26.478 --> 09:28.568
♪♪

09:28.611 --> 09:30.700
[ Exhales sharply ]
Try not to pass out this time.

09:30.744 --> 09:32.484
Ha, ha, very funny.

09:34.312 --> 09:35.705
Crap.
What is it?

09:35.749 --> 09:37.402
I can't donate.

09:37.446 --> 09:38.926
What? Why?

09:38.969 --> 09:41.189
Men who are sexually active
with other men

09:41.232 --> 09:43.147
in the last three months
are prohibited.

09:43.191 --> 09:46.890
And I wasn't active,
uh, the last time I donated.

09:46.934 --> 09:48.283
I wasn't even out.

09:48.326 --> 09:50.198
But what about gay women?They don't care.

09:50.241 --> 09:52.722
That is the most asinine thing
I have ever heard.
Shh!

09:52.766 --> 09:54.332
Please, it's fine.

09:54.376 --> 09:56.421
You and your blood are being
excluded for being gay.

09:56.465 --> 09:57.727
You should say something.

09:57.771 --> 09:59.294
Can I just keep my job,
please?

09:59.337 --> 10:00.817
Plus, it's almost been
three months

10:00.861 --> 10:02.297
since Nico and I broke up,
so I'll just --

10:02.340 --> 10:03.211
I'll do it then.

10:04.386 --> 10:05.909
[ Sighs ] Go.

10:10.871 --> 10:12.829
Woman: Know anything yet?

10:12.873 --> 10:14.570
Man: The doctor's
in with her now,

10:14.614 --> 10:15.527
so hopefully we'll have some
information soon.

10:15.571 --> 10:17.355
Who's this guy?

10:17.399 --> 10:18.922
Glen Sandstone.

10:18.966 --> 10:20.663
High-powered attorney.

10:20.707 --> 10:22.665
Nick: And he's married to
the blonde one here?

10:22.709 --> 10:25.842
No, no. Audrey, the Spanish
woman that has the twin sister.

10:25.886 --> 10:27.191
Ah, a twist.

10:27.235 --> 10:28.932
Didn't see that coming.

10:28.976 --> 10:30.630
Cora: She needs help remembering
her own name,

10:30.673 --> 10:32.719
but she has the entire town
of Gladwell's family tree

10:32.762 --> 10:33.807
committed to memory.

10:35.983 --> 10:38.420
Cora, I agree with Dr. Marsh.

10:38.463 --> 10:40.901
Yeah, normally
I love hearing that.

10:40.944 --> 10:43.425
We can try
a Whipple procedure,

10:43.468 --> 10:47.647
but we won't be able to get
100% of the tumor.

10:47.690 --> 10:49.344
But, i-it will help
with your pain

10:49.387 --> 10:52.129
and maybe even give you
some more time with your aunt.

10:52.173 --> 10:53.827
Hopefully.

10:53.870 --> 10:57.134
[ Chatter on television
continues]

10:57.178 --> 11:00.355
I take care of her now,
but...

11:00.398 --> 11:01.965
Sally raised me.

11:02.009 --> 11:03.750
My mom wanted to be
a good mother, in theory.

11:03.793 --> 11:06.013
But she had
other priorities.

11:06.056 --> 11:09.669
So when she would disappear
for days on end with a new guy,

11:09.712 --> 11:13.411
Sally would come,
make sure I was eating dinner,

11:13.455 --> 11:16.197
taking a bath,
tuck me in at night,

11:16.240 --> 11:18.068
and tell me
my mom had just called.

11:18.112 --> 11:19.679
I'd just missed her.

11:19.722 --> 11:22.072
But she called to tell me
she loves me.

11:22.116 --> 11:23.987
And it wasn't till my 20s
that I realized

11:24.031 --> 11:26.860
that Sally
was making it up.

11:26.903 --> 11:28.600
And thank God she did,
you know?

11:28.644 --> 11:31.691
Because it's better to miss
your mom than to hate her.

11:31.734 --> 11:33.257
And now she needs me.

11:35.172 --> 11:39.002
She needs me to feed her
and bathe her...

11:40.612 --> 11:42.266
...tell her
someone loves her.

11:44.225 --> 11:46.880
So I need something better
than hopefully...

11:49.099 --> 11:50.361
...and maybe.

11:50.405 --> 11:55.192
♪♪

11:55.236 --> 11:56.977
So Heather
is just walking around,

11:57.020 --> 11:58.805
advertising
that -- that you're

11:58.848 --> 12:00.458
the military's
concierge death doctor?

12:00.502 --> 12:01.808
Of course not.

12:01.851 --> 12:03.679
I tried calling her,
but she didn't answer.

12:03.723 --> 12:05.376
Until then, I don't know
what to do with this guy.

12:05.420 --> 12:07.074
What do you mean, what to do?
You tell him no.

12:07.117 --> 12:09.032
[ Whispering ]
Well, then...

12:09.076 --> 12:11.339
then he reports me,
and I go to jail.

12:11.382 --> 12:13.036
Owen, we don't even know
who this guy is.

12:13.080 --> 12:14.516
He could be lying
about his wife.

12:14.559 --> 12:15.691
I saw medical records.

12:15.735 --> 12:17.562
He could have
fabricated them!

12:17.606 --> 12:19.129
He could be a drug-seeker,
appealing specifically to you

12:19.173 --> 12:20.478
'cause he heard
what you did.

12:20.522 --> 12:22.089
Listen, he called her
on video-chat.

12:22.132 --> 12:23.351
We spoke.
[ Sighs ]

12:23.394 --> 12:24.874
Rosie's real, Teddy.

12:24.918 --> 12:27.355
She's really sick
and she just wants my help.

12:27.398 --> 12:29.139
[ Sighs ]
Listen, I --

12:29.183 --> 12:33.143
I can check the VA database,
confirm that she is military.

12:33.187 --> 12:34.492
That make you feel better?Yes.

12:34.536 --> 12:35.711
And if he's telling
the truth?

12:35.755 --> 12:37.539
We find another way
to help.

12:37.582 --> 12:46.548
♪♪

12:46.591 --> 12:48.855
Kristen: Help! Help!

12:48.898 --> 12:50.247
Dr. Lincoln, hurry!Link: What happened?!

12:50.291 --> 12:51.683
Please, it's Simon.
He can't --

12:51.727 --> 12:53.468
He's not breathing!
Winston!

12:53.511 --> 12:54.861
I'm scared
that he's dying!

12:54.904 --> 12:56.079
[ Monitor alarm ]

12:56.123 --> 12:58.299
[ Gasping ]

12:58.342 --> 13:01.519
♪♪

13:01.563 --> 13:02.825
Sats are plummeting,
despite his high-flow.

13:02.869 --> 13:04.218
BP's dropping, too.

13:04.261 --> 13:05.872
We're gonna have
to intubate you, Simon.

13:05.915 --> 13:08.526
No, I'm okay, just --
just keep the air coming.

13:08.570 --> 13:10.093
Don't intubate.

13:10.137 --> 13:12.095
Don't talk, babe.
Save your energy.

13:12.139 --> 13:14.663
If they put in the tube,
I may never wake up.

13:14.706 --> 13:15.969
Our son...

13:16.012 --> 13:17.753
[ Coughs ][ Monitor beeps ]

13:17.797 --> 13:19.320
Levi: Sats are in the 80s.

13:19.363 --> 13:21.452
His O2's maxed out.
What do you want to do?

13:21.496 --> 13:24.020
Kristen.

13:24.064 --> 13:25.369
Intubate him.

13:25.413 --> 13:27.807
Get the intubation tray.

13:27.850 --> 13:29.852
Woman: Coming through.

13:29.896 --> 13:31.549
We need
a size 8 ET tube.

13:31.593 --> 13:32.942
Get suction ready.

13:32.986 --> 13:36.990
♪♪

13:37.033 --> 13:37.991
Give me
some cricoid pressure.

13:44.998 --> 13:47.087
[ Indistinct conversations ]

13:47.130 --> 13:48.436
Maybe if we close
our eyes,

13:48.479 --> 13:49.916
it'll feel like
we're at the spa.

13:49.959 --> 13:53.310
Mm. Spas smell like
lavender and eucalyptus,

13:53.354 --> 13:55.182
not rubbing alcohol
and plastic.

13:55.225 --> 13:57.880
Also, people bring you things
to put over your eyes.

13:57.924 --> 13:59.926
This is not a spa.

13:59.969 --> 14:01.579
How are you?
Today should be

14:01.623 --> 14:03.625
one of the biggest
celebratory days of my career.

14:03.668 --> 14:05.105
Our article was published.

14:05.148 --> 14:06.889
I might have gotten
one step closer

14:06.933 --> 14:09.283
to surgically curing
Parkinson's disease.

14:09.326 --> 14:10.893
And all you can think about
is Kai.

14:10.937 --> 14:11.981
Have you heard from them?

14:12.025 --> 14:13.417
They texted,
"Thinking of you."

14:13.461 --> 14:15.724
Which is sweet,
but does nothing to soothe

14:15.767 --> 14:19.293
the intense ache
that is consuming my body.

14:19.336 --> 14:20.294
Breakups are hard.

14:20.337 --> 14:22.687
Give it time.

14:22.731 --> 14:24.298
Has Winston heard
from his brother?

14:24.341 --> 14:26.039
No.

14:26.082 --> 14:28.389
And, uh,
he's mildly obsessing.

14:28.432 --> 14:29.477
No -- not mildly.

14:29.520 --> 14:31.087
He is obsessing.

14:31.131 --> 14:32.872
And this morning I tried
to get him to let it go,

14:32.915 --> 14:34.482
and he responded by telling me
I don't know what it's like

14:34.525 --> 14:37.398
to have siblings.
Mm.

14:37.441 --> 14:38.529
What?
You agree with him?

14:38.573 --> 14:39.966
It's just --

14:40.009 --> 14:40.923
No, it's just,
it's different.

14:40.967 --> 14:42.229
I mean,
you and I are sisters

14:42.272 --> 14:45.188
in like the best
and most adult ways,

14:45.232 --> 14:47.495
and I love you.

14:47.538 --> 14:49.018
But my Shepherd sisters?

14:49.062 --> 14:51.020
When they get under my skin,
I cannot get them out,

14:51.064 --> 14:52.543
and I love them,

14:52.587 --> 14:54.197
but I'm not sure
that I like them.

14:54.241 --> 14:56.634
And that is just based in,
like, childhood stuff.

14:56.678 --> 14:57.853
So you agree with him.

14:57.897 --> 14:58.985
[ Chuckles ]
I'm saying,

14:59.028 --> 15:00.812
don't try to help him
stop obsessing.

15:00.856 --> 15:02.292
It is only gonna make him
obsess more.

15:02.336 --> 15:05.034
Here I thought I knew my husband
inside and out,

15:05.078 --> 15:08.168
and there's just a lo--
I mean...

15:08.211 --> 15:11.301
Deep things, like this thing
with his brother.

15:11.345 --> 15:12.868
[ Sighs ]

15:12.912 --> 15:14.087
A lot of stuff
I didn't anticipate,

15:14.130 --> 15:16.785
a lot of stuff that
I-I don't know.

15:20.571 --> 15:22.443
[ Whirring ]

15:24.445 --> 15:27.491
Hey. I, uh --
I heard about Simon.

15:27.535 --> 15:29.363
You okay?

15:29.406 --> 15:31.931
[ Sighs ] I'm just trying
to distract myself

15:31.974 --> 15:33.802
from thinking about
all the terrible things

15:33.845 --> 15:36.848
that are gonna appear
on this screen in two minutes.

15:36.892 --> 15:37.937
[ Sighs ]

15:37.980 --> 15:39.590
You break up
with Pavarotti?

15:39.634 --> 15:41.984
Really? You're thinking
about Todd right now?

15:42.028 --> 15:45.857
No, I'm thinking about how
I wish we had gone to karaoke

15:45.901 --> 15:47.294
the night the three of us
went out drinking.

15:47.337 --> 15:49.687
[ Laughs ]
I hate you.

15:49.731 --> 15:52.125
He's nice.
He's kind.

15:52.168 --> 15:54.910
But he is also obsessed
with his own PhD,

15:54.954 --> 15:58.479
and he narrates his life
out loud.

15:58.522 --> 16:01.482
Like, "And now,
I'm making the coffee.

16:01.525 --> 16:03.397
I'm putting the beans
in the filter.

16:03.440 --> 16:05.877
Now, I'm putting the water
in the pot."

16:05.921 --> 16:07.183
[ Laughs ]
That is --

16:07.227 --> 16:09.142
Enraging.
Yeah, it is.

16:09.185 --> 16:10.795
That...

16:10.839 --> 16:12.275
plus the singing orgasm --

16:12.319 --> 16:14.060
It's a lot.
Yeah.

16:14.103 --> 16:16.888
But he's --
Oh, he's so nice.

16:16.932 --> 16:18.847
♪ Figaro

16:18.890 --> 16:20.153
♪ Figaro

16:20.196 --> 16:22.372
♪ Figaro, Figaro No!

16:22.416 --> 16:23.983
[ Laughs ]

16:24.026 --> 16:25.114
[ Computer chirps ]

16:25.158 --> 16:27.116
Oh, damn it.

16:27.160 --> 16:30.859
♪♪

16:30.902 --> 16:32.208
Nick: Okay,
how about this?

16:32.252 --> 16:34.254
What if we resect
her entire pancreas,

16:34.297 --> 16:35.603
extract the islet cells,

16:35.646 --> 16:36.821
and insert them
into her liver

16:36.865 --> 16:39.041
so she can still
make insulin?

16:39.085 --> 16:40.825
Well, we said bold swings.
That's a bold swing.

16:40.869 --> 16:43.872
I havedone an islet cell
transplant before.

16:43.915 --> 16:45.395
Of course you have.
Of course.

16:45.439 --> 16:47.354
Are you impressed?I mean, impressed.

16:47.397 --> 16:49.051
I'm turned on.
I'm impressed, I'm turned on...

16:49.095 --> 16:50.792
[ Laughs ]

16:50.835 --> 16:53.360
I just wish there were a way
to just get in there

16:53.403 --> 16:56.145
and cut around the tumor
a little bit at a time,

16:56.189 --> 16:57.842
piece by piece.

16:57.886 --> 17:00.584
But how do we do that during
a critical blood shortage?

17:00.628 --> 17:02.804
Wait, she would lose
a lot less blood

17:02.847 --> 17:04.980
if we didn't do the surgery
inside the body.

17:05.024 --> 17:07.026
You want to do
an ex-vivo surgery?

17:07.069 --> 17:09.245
You've done one of those, too,
haven't you?

17:09.289 --> 17:10.899
[ Laughs ]
Right.

17:10.942 --> 17:12.509
Well, if we were going
to go that route,

17:12.553 --> 17:16.078
it would be helpful to have
an extra set of hands.

17:16.122 --> 17:18.211
So, basically,
you want to do a Whipple,

17:18.254 --> 17:21.257
but outside the body
on the back O.R. table?

17:21.301 --> 17:24.130
Exactly.
Remove everything involved --

17:24.173 --> 17:25.566
the liver,

17:25.609 --> 17:26.741
the pancreatic head
with the tumor,

17:26.784 --> 17:27.742
the intestines.

17:27.785 --> 17:29.135
Remove it all en bloc,

17:29.178 --> 17:30.962
excise the tumor,

17:31.006 --> 17:33.661
and then transplant everything
back into Cora's body.

17:33.704 --> 17:35.532
And whose idea
was this?

17:35.576 --> 17:37.099
Does it matter?

17:37.143 --> 17:39.754
No, it doesn't,
because it's a bad idea.

17:39.797 --> 17:41.103
I mean, it's too risky,

17:41.147 --> 17:42.887
and, frankly, today,
it's irresponsible.

17:42.931 --> 17:46.152
I mean, a surgery like this
would take over 20 hours.

17:46.195 --> 17:48.328
So we should, what,
send her home to die?

17:48.371 --> 17:50.460
Jamarah Blake is on her way
to decide

17:50.504 --> 17:54.073
whether or not this hospital can
continue its training program,

17:54.116 --> 17:56.771
because I was too confident and
tried to reinvent the wheel.

17:56.814 --> 17:58.338
Today is not the day
to go rogue.

18:01.080 --> 18:03.212
[ Sighs ]

18:03.256 --> 18:05.301
Maybe it isn't rogue,
maybe it's cutting edge.

18:05.345 --> 18:07.608
And maybe cutting edge
is exactly what we need to do

18:07.651 --> 18:10.611
to save the program.

18:10.654 --> 18:12.047
No, I'm sorry.

18:12.091 --> 18:15.137
I'm not gonna do it.

18:15.181 --> 18:18.445
♪♪

18:18.488 --> 18:21.143
Okay, um...well,
we can keep her admitted.

18:21.187 --> 18:22.666
I mean, we could do it
in a few days.

18:22.710 --> 18:24.668
Just because he screwed up
doesn't mean Cora has to die.

18:24.712 --> 18:25.756
I'm booking the O.R.

18:27.410 --> 18:28.411
Okay.

18:34.809 --> 18:36.593
Not only did the existing
lung mets grow,

18:36.637 --> 18:38.334
Simon now has more.

18:38.378 --> 18:40.336
So can we resect them?

18:40.380 --> 18:41.859
Unfortunately, no.

18:41.903 --> 18:43.165
Um, he already has
too much tumor burden.

18:43.209 --> 18:44.384
There won't be enough
pulmonary reserve.

18:44.427 --> 18:46.037
What about
a bronchial stent?

18:46.081 --> 18:48.170
Well, it's not a problem
of getting air into his lungs.

18:48.214 --> 18:49.867
It's a problem of getting them
to work at all.

18:49.911 --> 18:52.392
His wife
is 36 weeks pregnant.

18:52.435 --> 18:54.176
We just need him to hold on
long enough

18:54.220 --> 18:55.830
that she can have
a safe C-section.

18:58.267 --> 19:00.139
I told him
he'd meet his kid.

19:00.182 --> 19:02.837
Which, I know, I know,
it was stupid.

19:02.880 --> 19:04.621
[ Sighs ]

19:04.665 --> 19:06.275
What about ECMO?

19:06.319 --> 19:07.624
ECMO's not medically indicated
in this situation.

19:07.668 --> 19:09.452
Would it work?

19:09.496 --> 19:11.019
Well, come on.
Would it buy him some time?

19:11.062 --> 19:12.499
There are protocols
that we could follow

19:12.542 --> 19:14.414
in order to reduce
the amount of blood products.

19:14.457 --> 19:16.024
No, because what if
he bleeds out?

19:16.067 --> 19:18.592
Just come meet Kristen.

19:18.635 --> 19:20.898
Meet his wife. We can go over
these options together.

19:22.248 --> 19:23.423
[ Sighs ]

19:23.466 --> 19:24.989
Please.

19:25.033 --> 19:26.643
♪♪

19:26.687 --> 19:29.429
[ Sighs ]

19:29.472 --> 19:31.213
[ Elevator bell dings ]

19:31.257 --> 19:34.303
Uh, Ms. Blake, as, uh, director
of the residency program,

19:34.347 --> 19:36.087
I want you to know
that we have followed

19:36.131 --> 19:38.089
your recommendations
very seriously.

19:38.133 --> 19:39.656
Well,
I'm glad to hear it.

19:39.700 --> 19:41.484
[ Chuckles ]
Just in the past three weeks,

19:41.528 --> 19:43.704
we've hired
six new attendings,

19:43.747 --> 19:46.663
and teaching cases
have risen 40%.

19:46.707 --> 19:48.143
That's very impressive.

19:48.187 --> 19:49.449
I also read
the Parkinson's research

19:49.492 --> 19:51.407
of Doctors Grey
and Shepherd.

19:51.451 --> 19:53.192
It sounds like you've done
some groundbreaking work.

19:53.235 --> 19:54.976
Well, they have indeed.
[ Chuckles ]

19:55.019 --> 19:57.108
Well, this follow-up visit,
it shouldn't take long.

19:57.152 --> 19:58.806
I'll mostly be looking
to confirm

19:58.849 --> 20:00.895
that the issues that I flagged
have been addressed.

20:00.938 --> 20:03.245
Which it seems
that many of them have.

20:03.289 --> 20:05.116
You're almost done.Thank you.

20:05.160 --> 20:07.728
Are these
your residents?

20:07.771 --> 20:10.513
Hi.

20:10.557 --> 20:13.908
Ms. Blake, I am sure you are
aware that the state --

20:13.951 --> 20:16.302
the entire country,
for that matter --

20:16.345 --> 20:19.130
has been experiencing
a serious blood shortage.

20:19.174 --> 20:22.917
So we d-decided to take matters
into our own hands.

20:22.960 --> 20:27.008
By making your residents
donate blood during a shift?

20:27.051 --> 20:31.404
It -- This is
entirely voluntary.

20:31.447 --> 20:36.278
Well, are you gonna shut us down
for a nation-wide problem?

20:36.322 --> 20:37.540
[ Scoffs ]

20:40.239 --> 20:43.285
[ Monitor beeping ]

20:43.329 --> 20:45.635
So it moves the blood
out of his body

20:45.679 --> 20:49.248
and oxygenates it so he doesn't
have to use his lungs?

20:49.291 --> 20:52.120
That's right, it bypasses
his heart and lungs.

20:52.163 --> 20:53.121
Okay.

20:53.164 --> 20:54.862
Um, let's do that,
then.

20:54.905 --> 20:58.387
Kristen, ECMO comes
with its own complications.

20:58.431 --> 21:01.434
Particularly, it comes
with the risk of blood clots.

21:01.477 --> 21:03.871
So, he could...

21:03.914 --> 21:05.525
die more quickly.

21:05.568 --> 21:07.744
Kristen, we usually use ECMO
on patients

21:07.788 --> 21:11.357
so that their heart and lungs
can rest and recover.

21:11.400 --> 21:13.837
And Simon's lungs
are not going to recover.

21:13.881 --> 21:16.362
So what worries me about
using ECMO in this case

21:16.405 --> 21:17.537
is that at some point --

21:17.580 --> 21:18.886
We would have
to unplug him.

21:18.929 --> 21:20.583
At some point, yes.

21:20.627 --> 21:22.759
And that might be harder
than you --

21:22.803 --> 21:24.805
It won't be.

21:24.848 --> 21:26.981
It won't be harder.

21:27.024 --> 21:29.549
I mean, honestly,
it's all hard.

21:29.592 --> 21:30.941
It's more than hard.

21:30.985 --> 21:33.901
It's, um --
it's all impossible.

21:33.944 --> 21:37.383
But here we are anyway.
Right?

21:37.426 --> 21:40.951
Simon wants me to be able
to tell our son that they met.

21:40.995 --> 21:43.084
♪ Wait until the sun
goes down ♪

21:43.127 --> 21:47.131
That his dad loved him
beyond the beyond.

21:47.175 --> 21:48.872
We've talked about this
for months.

21:48.916 --> 21:50.091
♪ And you can see the stars

21:50.134 --> 21:52.311
We've talked about everything,
forever.

21:52.354 --> 21:56.271
We're -- We're talkers,
we're planners.

21:56.315 --> 21:59.535
We had so many plans.

21:59.579 --> 22:00.710
♪ You know exactly
where they are ♪

22:00.754 --> 22:01.755
And we don't get
to have them.

22:01.798 --> 22:04.323
♪ Even galaxies apart

22:04.366 --> 22:05.585
But if we could
have this...

22:05.628 --> 22:08.239
♪ They'll stay forever

22:08.283 --> 22:10.372
♪ Just know
they're never too far ♪

22:10.416 --> 22:12.374
I mean, obviously,
we didn't talk about ECMO.

22:12.418 --> 22:14.681
We didn't talk about
this specific, impossible thing.

22:14.724 --> 22:16.900
But I know my husband.

22:18.598 --> 22:22.819
I know him better
than I know myself.

22:22.863 --> 22:25.822
I'm fine with the fact
that it might be harder on me.

22:25.866 --> 22:28.651
If I have to...

22:28.695 --> 22:32.046
say goodbye
and unplug him...

22:34.309 --> 22:36.877
...it will be just one more
impossible thing.

22:36.920 --> 22:40.663
♪♪

22:40.707 --> 22:43.666
But at least
he will have met his son.

22:45.712 --> 22:49.977
♪ It's the letting go
that lets you fly ♪

22:50.020 --> 22:50.978
Yes.

22:51.021 --> 22:51.979
♪ Lets you fly

22:52.022 --> 22:54.198
I say yes.

22:54.242 --> 22:55.896
Okay. Let's do it.
Let's try it.

22:57.332 --> 22:58.420
♪ Getting darker now

22:58.464 --> 23:00.422
Let's try.

23:00.466 --> 23:03.817
♪♪

23:03.860 --> 23:07.124
♪ But the sky
is full of lights ♪

23:07.168 --> 23:08.430
Nick: Cora, we just want
to make sure

23:08.474 --> 23:10.084
that you understand
the surgery

23:10.127 --> 23:12.521
and how complicated
it will be.

23:12.565 --> 23:14.393
♪ But you can't hold
something bright ♪

23:14.436 --> 23:16.873
[ Sighs ]

23:16.917 --> 23:18.440
♪ Even in the darkest night It's different
when it's you.

23:18.484 --> 23:20.355
I'm sorry?

23:20.399 --> 23:22.836
I'm so used to taking Sally
to all her appointments and...

23:22.879 --> 23:24.925
♪ Just know
they're never too far ♪

23:24.968 --> 23:27.449
...so many doctors
and so many hospitals.

23:27.493 --> 23:28.842
♪ They'll keep us together

23:28.885 --> 23:30.670
When it's you,
it's -- it's different.

23:30.713 --> 23:33.673
Sharper focus.
More frightening.

23:33.716 --> 23:35.065
Cora, we're gonna take
great care of you

23:35.109 --> 23:36.676
no matter
what you decide.

23:36.719 --> 23:39.026
But I don't know
what happens to Sally if I die.

23:39.069 --> 23:42.856
I mean, she's confused if
I'm gone for just five minutes.

23:42.899 --> 23:46.033
I know this surgery
sounds really risky.

23:46.076 --> 23:48.078
But in
my professional opinion,

23:48.122 --> 23:51.473
it is your only chance
of survival.

23:51.517 --> 23:52.953
Worst-case scenario?

23:52.996 --> 23:54.650
You could have
organ damage.

23:54.694 --> 23:55.956
You could bleed
too much.

23:55.999 --> 23:57.958
You could die.And soon.

23:58.001 --> 24:00.090
Cora, you've put off
your own health

24:00.134 --> 24:01.875
for a really long time.

24:01.918 --> 24:04.312
And I think if Sally
could remember who you are,

24:04.355 --> 24:06.357
she would tell you that
in order to take care of her,

24:06.401 --> 24:09.317
you have to first
take care of yourself.

24:09.360 --> 24:16.585
♪♪

24:16.629 --> 24:17.978
Sally.

24:19.762 --> 24:21.329
Oh, love.

24:21.372 --> 24:22.461
That's for you.

24:22.504 --> 24:24.332
Yeah.

24:24.375 --> 24:27.944
♪ It's the letting go
that lets you fly ♪

24:27.988 --> 24:29.250
Okay, yeah.

24:29.293 --> 24:31.644
Let's do the surgery.

24:31.687 --> 24:32.645
Yeah.
[ Sniffles ]

24:32.688 --> 24:35.735
♪ Lets you fly

24:35.778 --> 24:37.345
Good.
Okay.

24:37.388 --> 24:38.955
Yeah.

24:38.999 --> 24:43.133
♪ It's the letting go
that lets you fly ♪

24:43.177 --> 24:46.354
[ Thunder crashes ]

24:46.397 --> 24:48.878
[ Siren wails in distance ]

24:50.576 --> 24:51.968
John.

24:56.016 --> 24:57.931
We're going
to help you.

24:57.974 --> 25:00.020
Oh, thank God.

25:00.063 --> 25:03.937
But it's, uh --
it's complicated.

25:03.980 --> 25:06.853
First, we're going to relocate
you and Rosie to Washington.

25:06.896 --> 25:08.028
We're going to set you up
with housing

25:08.071 --> 25:09.856
and vouch
that you're current residents.

25:09.899 --> 25:11.422
And then we'll file
all the paperwork

25:11.466 --> 25:13.729
to show
Rosie's service record

25:13.773 --> 25:17.124
and that she qualifies
for physician-assisted death.

25:17.167 --> 25:18.647
Teddy: We're willing to help
with the costs

25:18.691 --> 25:21.258
and make sure that Rosie
has all the medications and care

25:21.302 --> 25:23.130
required to keep her
as comfortable as possible.

25:23.173 --> 25:24.871
Stop. That's --
That's not why I came here.

25:24.914 --> 25:26.046
That's not
what I asked you for.

25:26.089 --> 25:27.395
We understand that,
but --

25:27.438 --> 25:28.788
John, we haven't assessed
your wife.

25:28.831 --> 25:31.225
To give any medications
to a patient

25:31.268 --> 25:34.054
that you haven't seen,
it's just -- it's...

25:34.097 --> 25:36.970
It's not ethical.Not ethical to who?

25:37.013 --> 25:39.450
Some committee?

25:39.494 --> 25:42.410
Some spreadsheet that
tells you what's allowed?

25:42.453 --> 25:44.891
John --My wife is dying.

25:44.934 --> 25:47.894
She's not going to relocate
and fill out paperwork

25:47.937 --> 25:50.244
and be vouched for
by strangers.

25:50.287 --> 25:53.247
Rosie wants it to look like
she just died in her bed.

25:53.290 --> 25:56.293
She doesn't want our children
to know she took pills.

25:56.337 --> 25:59.079
That's what matters to her
more than anything.

25:59.122 --> 26:00.863
My wife is in pain

26:00.907 --> 26:03.562
and you're talking to me
about ethics?!

26:03.605 --> 26:04.606
[ Thunder crashes ]

26:04.650 --> 26:08.349
♪♪

26:08.392 --> 26:09.568
Heather told me
you're veterans.

26:11.134 --> 26:12.222
What about honor?

26:13.963 --> 26:16.400
Let Rosie die
with the dignity and honor

26:16.444 --> 26:18.359
she lived with, please.

26:18.402 --> 26:21.405
♪♪

26:21.449 --> 26:22.711
Please.

26:22.755 --> 26:24.278
[ Sighs ]

26:24.321 --> 26:25.888
Maybe there's a way --No.

26:25.932 --> 26:29.326
No, I am truly,
deeply sorry, John.

26:29.370 --> 26:31.111
I-I wish there was more
that we could do,

26:31.154 --> 26:33.548
but to what you are asking,
the answer is no.

26:33.592 --> 26:34.593
We just can't.

26:34.636 --> 26:40.511
♪♪

26:40.555 --> 26:43.340
[ Thunder crashes ]

26:43.384 --> 26:47.736
♪♪

26:54.613 --> 26:55.875
[ Monitor beeping ]

26:55.918 --> 26:57.528
Okay. [ Sighs ]

26:57.572 --> 26:59.530
And there it is.

26:59.574 --> 27:01.924
It involves the entire
hepatoduodenal ligament.

27:01.968 --> 27:03.796
We sure we want
to keep going here?

27:04.710 --> 27:07.016
[ Suction ]

27:07.060 --> 27:08.365
We can do this.

27:08.409 --> 27:09.845
What other choice
does she have?

27:09.889 --> 27:12.152
Let's mobilize
the right colon first.

27:12.195 --> 27:13.632
Okay.

27:13.675 --> 27:15.285
Hyper vigilant
on the suction, Helm.

27:15.329 --> 27:17.157
We need to send
every drop of blood Cora loses

27:17.200 --> 27:20.116
into the cell saver so we can
transfuse it back into her.

27:23.467 --> 27:31.737
♪♪

27:31.780 --> 27:33.347
Wait, when Dr. Webber
said no,

27:33.390 --> 27:34.565
did he mean that he wouldn't do
the surgery

27:34.609 --> 27:37.220
or that no one should do
the surgery?

27:38.482 --> 27:39.614
Suction, Helm.

27:39.658 --> 27:44.837
♪♪

27:44.880 --> 27:47.230
[ Machines hissing, beeping ]

27:47.274 --> 27:48.710
Hello, forever.

27:51.321 --> 27:53.846
We used to live
in this two-story townhome

27:53.889 --> 27:59.242
that had an upstairs office that
I was convinced was haunted.

27:59.286 --> 28:01.070
And every time
I would go upstairs to work,

28:01.114 --> 28:04.073
Simon would say,
"Goodbye, forever."

28:04.117 --> 28:06.206
[ Chuckles ]

28:07.511 --> 28:08.991
It always made me laugh...

28:10.906 --> 28:13.213
...until his diagnosis.

28:13.256 --> 28:17.565
I told him that I didn't want
to hear that anymore,

28:17.608 --> 28:20.742
and suddenly...

28:20.786 --> 28:22.570
instead of "Goodbye"...

28:24.137 --> 28:25.878
...it was "Hello."

28:25.921 --> 28:31.753
♪♪

28:31.797 --> 28:34.016
I'm ready.

28:34.060 --> 28:36.279
♪♪

28:36.323 --> 28:38.064
[ Sighs ]

28:38.107 --> 28:40.109
[ "Hold the Line" by AG x
Daniel Saint Black playing ]

28:40.153 --> 28:41.241
Start prepping him.
Let's move.

28:41.284 --> 28:43.504
♪ It's a hard thing

28:43.547 --> 28:46.159
♪ To learn

28:46.202 --> 28:50.163
♪ Growing up on your own

28:50.206 --> 28:51.904
Meredith: We should hang
another unit of blood.

28:51.947 --> 28:53.688
♪ It's a river rising

28:53.732 --> 28:56.647
Nick: Okay, everything
is clamped off and divided.

28:56.691 --> 28:58.475
On my count.

28:58.519 --> 29:01.348
One, two...

29:01.391 --> 29:02.915
three.

29:02.958 --> 29:04.786
Oh, my God, oh, my God,
oh, my God.

29:04.830 --> 29:06.353
♪ I will hold the line

29:06.396 --> 29:07.571
Perfect.

29:07.615 --> 29:08.572
Got it?

29:08.616 --> 29:10.183
♪ Always hold the line

29:10.226 --> 29:12.576
Admit it. Parkinson's
seems boring after this.

29:12.620 --> 29:14.100
♪ When you're feeling down

29:14.143 --> 29:17.581
♪ And the world's not right

29:17.625 --> 29:20.802
♪ And I know in time

29:20.846 --> 29:23.674
♪ It will be alright

29:23.718 --> 29:26.982
♪ But until then

29:27.026 --> 29:30.464
♪ I will hold the line

29:30.507 --> 29:32.422
♪ Hold the line

29:32.466 --> 29:36.818
♪♪

29:36.862 --> 29:39.168
♪ Hold the line

29:39.212 --> 29:43.085
♪♪

29:43.129 --> 29:49.831
♪ I can't say
I've got all the answers ♪

29:49.875 --> 29:54.357
♪ But I'm here all the same

29:54.401 --> 30:01.669
♪♪

30:01.712 --> 30:09.416
♪♪

30:09.459 --> 30:16.162
♪ I can't say
I've got all the answers ♪

30:16.205 --> 30:20.819
♪ But I'm here all the same

30:20.862 --> 30:22.037
Link: You need
to eat something.

30:23.386 --> 30:25.780
♪ Maybe we're outnumbered

30:25.824 --> 30:27.173
Am I selfish?

30:27.216 --> 30:29.740
♪ And we don't have much time

30:29.784 --> 30:31.742
Putting him through this?

30:31.786 --> 30:35.442
♪ Always hold the line

30:35.485 --> 30:38.445
♪ When you're feeling down

30:38.488 --> 30:41.361
♪ And the world's not right My son...

30:41.404 --> 30:44.843
The first time I saw him,
screaming his lungs out,

30:44.886 --> 30:47.889
it was like my heart
left my body.

30:47.933 --> 30:51.893
The amount of love I experienced
in that second...

30:51.937 --> 30:53.590
♪♪

30:53.634 --> 30:54.896
♪ The line

30:54.940 --> 30:56.202
Levi: His heart rate's
increasing.

30:56.245 --> 30:57.725
Winston: Some bleeding
over here. 4x4.

30:57.768 --> 30:59.161
Maggie: My incision is starting
to ooze, too.

30:59.205 --> 31:00.902
We need push
half a dose of protamine.

31:00.946 --> 31:02.512
BP's dropping.

31:02.556 --> 31:03.513
Link: ...I didn't care
what happened to me

31:03.557 --> 31:04.601
for the rest of my life.

31:04.645 --> 31:06.038
We need to work faster.

31:06.081 --> 31:07.691
Without adequate access,
there's no ECMO.

31:07.735 --> 31:08.823
Tube.

31:08.867 --> 31:10.259
♪ The line

31:10.303 --> 31:11.870
Alright.

31:11.913 --> 31:14.742
Remove the clamps.

31:14.785 --> 31:17.005
♪ Hold the line

31:17.049 --> 31:18.398
Come on, Simon.

31:18.441 --> 31:20.400
♪ Ooh

31:20.443 --> 31:23.882
♪ It's a river rising Come on. Come on.

31:23.925 --> 31:27.276
♪ A hundred stones

31:27.320 --> 31:29.061
♪ You don't have...

31:29.104 --> 31:30.192
That...

31:30.236 --> 31:32.020
♪ ...to face them alone

31:32.064 --> 31:33.326
That was enough.

31:33.369 --> 31:36.503
♪ I will hold the line

31:36.546 --> 31:38.984
♪♪

31:39.027 --> 31:43.466
♪ Hold the line

31:43.510 --> 31:46.295
Bailey: That blood should have
been here over an hour ago!

31:46.339 --> 31:47.470
Woman: [ Over P.A. ]
Dr. Mari Sellers 4619.
Dr. Mari Sellers 4619.

31:47.514 --> 31:51.039
It rains
approximately 150 days a year.

31:51.083 --> 31:53.520
Are you actually telling me
that no one has had to drive

31:53.563 --> 31:56.175
a shipment of blood
in the damn rain?

31:56.218 --> 31:58.307
What -- Okay, well,
can I pick it up myself?

31:58.351 --> 32:01.267
My blood is just as helpful
as anyone else's.

32:01.310 --> 32:03.965
It has plasma
and red blood cells

32:04.009 --> 32:05.836
and white blood cells
and platelets and --

32:05.880 --> 32:06.968
W--
Let me call you back.

32:07.012 --> 32:08.404
[ Cellphone beeps ]

32:08.448 --> 32:10.798
I have donated blood
to this hospital before.

32:10.841 --> 32:12.060
Many times.

32:12.104 --> 32:14.889
And I just saw
units of blood

32:14.933 --> 32:16.717
circulating
into an ECMO machine,

32:16.760 --> 32:18.588
and I know that we can use
every drop we have.

32:18.632 --> 32:19.850
And I can't help.

32:19.894 --> 32:21.983
I can't help because
of this...prejudice.

32:22.027 --> 32:25.944
This absurd, disgusting idea
that my blood --

32:25.987 --> 32:28.859
my sexually active
gay blood -- is...

32:31.340 --> 32:34.343
My blood is the same
as it's always been.

32:34.387 --> 32:35.562
It's -- I-I know.

32:35.605 --> 32:37.303
And it is not right.

32:37.346 --> 32:39.696
It is very, very wrong.

32:39.740 --> 32:41.960
And if I were in charge
of the rules,

32:42.003 --> 32:44.527
we wouldn't be having
this conversation.

32:44.571 --> 32:45.311
So can I help?

32:45.354 --> 32:46.747
No, Schmitt.

32:46.790 --> 32:48.357
[ Sighs ]
I'm sorry.

32:48.401 --> 32:51.360
But look, you help this hospital
in so many other ways.

32:53.406 --> 32:54.363
Okay.

32:54.407 --> 32:55.495
Schmitt --

32:55.538 --> 32:58.106
♪♪

32:58.150 --> 33:00.369
[ Sighs ]

33:00.413 --> 33:01.457
Great.

33:01.501 --> 33:02.937
[ Sighs ]

33:02.981 --> 33:04.765
[ Knock on door ]John: 'Scuse me.

33:04.808 --> 33:06.593
Are you Chief of Surgery?

33:06.636 --> 33:09.378
Uh, y-- I am, but right now
I'm in the middle of --

33:09.422 --> 33:12.425
I need to report a crime
one of your doctors committed.

33:12.468 --> 33:14.209
♪♪

33:20.607 --> 33:21.869
[ Telephone rings ]

33:21.912 --> 33:23.175
Hey! I got a --

33:23.218 --> 33:25.133
No.

33:25.177 --> 33:26.265
Not a good time?

33:26.308 --> 33:28.049
Not a good...bear?

33:28.093 --> 33:30.747
[ Chuckles ]Not a good match.

33:32.619 --> 33:34.360
But we had sex.

33:35.839 --> 33:37.406
We did.

33:37.450 --> 33:40.279
And I-I'm so sorry, but
y-you said that you loved me.

33:40.322 --> 33:44.805
And I think I might see this
as more casual than you do.

33:44.848 --> 33:46.937
I'm so sorry, Todd,

33:46.981 --> 33:48.591
but, please,
give the bear to your sister.

33:48.635 --> 33:50.115
Well, it's a sex bear.

33:50.158 --> 33:52.552
It's a "thank you
for the excellent sex" bear.

33:52.595 --> 33:54.336
Does it say that
somewhere on it?

33:54.380 --> 33:56.338
Well, no.

33:56.382 --> 33:58.253
Then maybe
it's just a bear.

34:01.517 --> 34:02.649
Okay, I'm sorry.

34:02.692 --> 34:05.608
Um...bye.

34:11.353 --> 34:13.051
Hey, would you like
a sex bear?

34:13.094 --> 34:15.183
Or just --
I guess it's a bear?

34:18.404 --> 34:20.145
[ Sighs ]

34:20.188 --> 34:21.885
Richard: Only a few people
at Grey-Sloan

34:21.929 --> 34:24.323
have successfully performed
ex-vivo surgeries.

34:24.366 --> 34:26.499
Well, then, you're lucky
that Dr. Marsh joined the team.

34:26.542 --> 34:28.109
[ Chuckles ]And Dr. Grey is amazing.

34:28.153 --> 34:29.545
Oh, of course.

34:29.589 --> 34:31.330
I'm so glad she decided
to postpone leaving.

34:34.898 --> 34:39.294
Um, oh -- If you watch
Dr. Marsh here anastomose --

34:39.338 --> 34:41.557
Dr. Grey is leaving?

34:41.601 --> 34:42.819
Since when?

34:44.473 --> 34:46.214
[ Sighs ]

34:49.174 --> 34:51.219
Meredith: Okay, Helm.
We're done here.

34:51.263 --> 34:54.092
You do the honors and bring
the liver to Dr. Marsh.

34:54.135 --> 34:55.571
Absolutely, yes.

34:55.615 --> 34:58.922
[ Monitor beeping ]

34:58.966 --> 35:00.228
I approve.

35:00.272 --> 35:01.447
What's that?

35:01.490 --> 35:03.275
Uh, you and Grey?
Uh, Dr. Grey.

35:03.318 --> 35:06.016
I -- Sorry -- Never mind.
Here.

35:06.060 --> 35:07.409
Meredith: Ready to do
your thing?

35:07.453 --> 35:09.019
Nick:
She's stable and ready.

35:09.063 --> 35:11.152
Let's make
this old liver new again.

35:11.196 --> 35:16.157
♪♪

35:16.201 --> 35:17.550
Kristen: Simon.

35:17.593 --> 35:19.334
Hello, forever.

35:19.378 --> 35:24.426
♪♪

35:24.470 --> 35:25.775
How are you feeling?

35:25.819 --> 35:27.560
Better
now that you're here.

35:27.603 --> 35:28.909
♪ Heart on the edge

35:28.952 --> 35:32.565
And...I dreamed up a name
for the baby.

35:32.608 --> 35:33.609
♪ It's bound to break

35:33.653 --> 35:36.177
Jamal.

35:36.221 --> 35:38.875
I love it.
Mm-hmm.

35:38.919 --> 35:40.181
After your uncle?

35:40.225 --> 35:41.226
♪ There's silence in my head

35:41.269 --> 35:42.836
No.

35:42.879 --> 35:45.404
After you.

35:45.447 --> 35:48.711
It means "beauty."

35:48.755 --> 35:50.713
[ Chuckles ]

35:50.757 --> 35:56.328
♪♪

35:56.371 --> 36:01.202
♪ Oh, the stars
are getting dark tonight ♪

36:01.246 --> 36:02.812
♪ Waters rising

36:02.856 --> 36:05.206
♪ Fires dying

36:05.250 --> 36:07.513
♪ And here we stand

36:07.556 --> 36:09.428
♪ At the end

36:09.471 --> 36:11.865
Maggie:
What's your blood type?

36:11.908 --> 36:13.432
What?

36:13.475 --> 36:15.390
I'm your wife, and I don't know
your blood type,

36:15.434 --> 36:17.218
and I feel like
that's weird.

36:17.262 --> 36:18.219
O Positive.

36:18.263 --> 36:19.307
A Positive.

36:19.351 --> 36:20.874
Okay.

36:20.917 --> 36:22.136
Noted.

36:22.180 --> 36:23.311
♪ At the end

36:23.355 --> 36:27.707
♪♪

36:27.750 --> 36:29.361
Sometimes I-I feel like...

36:31.276 --> 36:33.887
...I feel like we knew
each other better before...

36:36.019 --> 36:37.891
...when our relationship
was long distance.

36:39.327 --> 36:41.286
Because of blood types?

36:41.329 --> 36:43.636
Because I'm constantly being
surprised by things about you

36:43.679 --> 36:47.074
and decisions you make.

36:47.117 --> 36:50.643
Like everything you never
told me about your brother,

36:50.686 --> 36:53.428
and how it makes you angrier
than I think you realize.

36:53.472 --> 36:55.300
I'm not --
I'm not angry.

36:55.343 --> 36:56.736
I...

36:56.779 --> 36:58.259
♪ Lying here in this hurt

36:58.303 --> 37:00.522
I-I amangry,
but I'm not angry with you.

37:00.566 --> 37:02.655
This morning, you implied
that I don't know

37:02.698 --> 37:03.873
what it's like
to have a sibling.

37:03.917 --> 37:05.310
No, I didn't.
I didn't.

37:05.353 --> 37:06.485
I said -- I said
it was different.

37:06.528 --> 37:08.530
It isdifferent.

37:08.574 --> 37:09.792
You can't see that?

37:09.836 --> 37:11.185
I guess I don't know
what it's like

37:11.229 --> 37:12.969
to have a sibling
who's a con artist.

37:13.013 --> 37:15.102
♪ It's the bed that we made

37:15.145 --> 37:16.799
Why are you making this
a fight between us?

37:16.843 --> 37:18.497
It's not a fight.It's not a fight.

37:18.540 --> 37:21.804
♪ Oh, the stars
are getting dark tonight ♪

37:21.848 --> 37:24.198
I guess I just feel like,
um...

37:24.242 --> 37:26.853
♪ Waters rising

37:26.896 --> 37:28.985
...like I don't know you.

37:29.029 --> 37:30.291
♪ At the end

37:30.335 --> 37:31.988
And that you don't
really get me.

37:32.032 --> 37:34.556
♪ Oh, you know that you can't
hide from time ♪

37:34.600 --> 37:35.775
[ Sighs ]

37:35.818 --> 37:37.298
Winston, I love you.
I...

37:37.342 --> 37:39.822
♪ And denied it

37:39.866 --> 37:41.128
I think maybe...

37:41.171 --> 37:42.390
♪ Here we stand

37:42.434 --> 37:45.393
♪ At the end

37:45.437 --> 37:47.700
Maybe we got married
too quickly.

37:47.743 --> 37:49.136
♪♪

37:49.179 --> 37:51.312
♪ At the end

37:51.356 --> 37:55.795
♪♪

37:55.838 --> 37:57.449
[ Thunder crashes ]

37:57.492 --> 37:59.320
Can you stop pacing
and help me pack?

37:59.364 --> 38:00.713
I'm trying
to call Heather again.

38:00.756 --> 38:01.931
Heather made this mess.

38:01.975 --> 38:03.498
She's not gonna get you
out of it.

38:03.542 --> 38:04.934
Well, maybe she can try.
Or maybe --

38:04.978 --> 38:06.371
Maybe -- Maybe --
Maybe what?

38:06.414 --> 38:07.589
Maybe we can
go back in time

38:07.633 --> 38:09.678
and help you
not destroy your career?

38:09.722 --> 38:11.027
Well, maybe I can go to Utah
and...

38:11.071 --> 38:12.551
Oh!...and I can help his wife.

38:12.594 --> 38:14.204
She is a soldier, Teddy.

38:14.248 --> 38:16.598
She served our country
and she deserves help!

38:16.642 --> 38:17.947
Owen, I love you.

38:17.991 --> 38:20.036
I love you
and your stupid, giant heart

38:20.080 --> 38:22.387
and your --
your intense inability

38:22.430 --> 38:25.781
to see reality when you're busy
believing your ideals.

38:25.825 --> 38:28.306
I love every part of you.

38:28.349 --> 38:30.177
But I am not gonna watch you
go off to prison,

38:30.220 --> 38:31.787
and I am not gonna
raise the kids alone.

38:31.831 --> 38:33.049
I'm not.So where are we going?

38:33.093 --> 38:34.747
What are we doing?
We're running?

38:34.790 --> 38:37.227
Yes, we are running because that
is the only option you left us.

38:37.271 --> 38:38.446
♪ At the end

38:42.407 --> 38:44.017
Please...

38:44.060 --> 38:47.237
tell me a lunatic
just entered my office

38:47.281 --> 38:50.371
and told me ridiculous lies
about you.

38:50.415 --> 38:53.548
Please, tell me I need
to call the police on him,

38:53.592 --> 38:55.811
and not my own doctors.

38:55.855 --> 39:02.209
♪♪

39:02.252 --> 39:05.212
You can take the specimen
to pathology. Thank you.

39:05.255 --> 39:09.303
We have reperfusion of
the intestines and the liver.

39:09.347 --> 39:10.739
Okay.

39:10.783 --> 39:11.697
Where's this blood
coming from?

39:11.740 --> 39:12.872
[ Monitor alarm ]

39:12.915 --> 39:14.656
It's the portal vein --
anastomosis.

39:14.700 --> 39:16.702
She's lost too much.
We need to order more units.

39:16.745 --> 39:19.444
Clamp. The transfusions
aren't keeping up. BP's dropping.

39:19.487 --> 39:21.837
You stole drugs
from this hospital?

39:21.881 --> 39:23.404
I stand by my decision,
Bailey.

39:23.448 --> 39:27.060
You stand by your decision
to steal drugs from my hospital?

39:27.103 --> 39:28.627
A hospital
that's already crumbling?

39:28.670 --> 39:30.019
It was a while ago --

39:30.063 --> 39:31.891
Oh! Well, that makes it better.
[ Chuckles ]

39:31.934 --> 39:35.024
Your criminal conduct
on my watch was a while ago!

39:35.068 --> 39:36.112
Meredith: Okay,
we still have to do

39:36.156 --> 39:37.287
the gastrointestinal
reconstruction.

39:37.331 --> 39:38.288
Taryn: Is there a plan?

39:38.332 --> 39:39.507
Of course there's a plan.

39:39.551 --> 39:41.161
What's her latest ABG?

39:41.204 --> 39:42.945
Dr. Knox: She's acidotic,
and PaO2 is plummeting.

39:42.989 --> 39:44.251
What about pressors? Maxed out.

39:44.294 --> 39:46.471
Was it so long ago that
it's outside

39:46.514 --> 39:47.863
the statute
of limitations?

39:47.907 --> 39:48.690
Bailey.[ Cellphone rings ]

39:48.734 --> 39:50.257
D--
[ Ends call ]

39:50.300 --> 39:52.868
What is the statute
of limitations on murder?

39:52.912 --> 39:54.479
Huh?
D-Did you look that up

39:54.522 --> 39:55.784
before you committed
your crimes?

39:55.828 --> 39:56.916
This wasn't murder,
Bailey.

39:56.959 --> 39:58.831
These were
sick and dying soldiers.

39:58.874 --> 40:01.050
They fought for their country,
and I did right by them.

40:01.094 --> 40:03.052
You did right by them.
Well, what about me?

40:03.096 --> 40:05.707
Did you think,
even for one minute, about me?

40:05.751 --> 40:06.839
Taryn: Dr. Grey,
what are we doing?

40:06.882 --> 40:08.493
[ Monitor alarm ]

40:08.536 --> 40:11.844
Ellis: That's what everyone
wants in a surgeon.

40:11.887 --> 40:13.672
Someone who maybe knows
what they're doing.

40:13.715 --> 40:16.631
Always have a plan.
I told you that.

40:16.675 --> 40:18.111
Nick: Meredith.
Meredith.

40:18.154 --> 40:20.330
[ Alarm continues ]

40:20.374 --> 40:24.857
♪♪

40:24.900 --> 40:26.032
We should stop.What?!

40:26.075 --> 40:27.773
We need blood.
We don't have it.

40:27.816 --> 40:28.556
So we should stop.

40:28.600 --> 40:30.079
[ Cellphone rings ]

40:30.123 --> 40:31.341
Is everything okay?

40:31.385 --> 40:32.386
I'm at an accident.

40:32.430 --> 40:33.735
On Henderson.

40:33.779 --> 40:35.650
Were you inthe accident?

40:35.694 --> 40:37.522
No. But you kinda were.

40:37.565 --> 40:40.220
Her digestive tract still
isn't completely connected.

40:40.263 --> 40:42.135
We'll reconnect it
once the blood arrives.

40:42.178 --> 40:43.484
Meredith: We've all felt it,

40:43.528 --> 40:45.051
a moment where all is lost.

40:45.094 --> 40:46.922
What? Whether it's in our jobs...

40:46.966 --> 40:48.489
Your blood, Miranda.

40:48.533 --> 40:49.751
It's trashed.

40:49.795 --> 40:51.492
...family, love...

40:51.536 --> 40:55.017
No. ...we fear everything
will be taken.

40:55.061 --> 40:56.279
No! We close our eyes...

40:56.323 --> 40:57.367
No! ...we bite our lips...

40:57.411 --> 40:59.457
No! No!

40:59.500 --> 41:01.502
...and the adrenaline floods
through our body.

41:01.546 --> 41:03.461
[ Siren wails ] But despite how hard you try,

41:03.504 --> 41:06.159
that last-ditch attempt
still may not work.

41:06.202 --> 41:09.989
No, no, no, no,
no, no, no!

41:10.032 --> 41:15.081
[ Siren wailing ]

41:25.134 --> 41:32.968
♪♪

41:33.012 --> 41:40.846
♪♪

41:40.889 --> 41:48.810
♪♪
